were with their job.

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:09.070
How engaged they were.

00:11:09.070 --> 00:11:11.780
And about 70% of the people
who responded to this survey

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:16.430
and participated said they
were not engaged at work.

00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:22.140
About 30% of that number said
they were actively disengaged.

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:24.230
Actively disengaged.

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:25.910
That means you're
not even faking

00:11:25.910 --> 00:11:27.530
being interested in
what you're doing.

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:27.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:27.830 --> 00:11:28.850
That's what that means.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:30.630
That means you're
like a brain surgeon

00:11:30.630 --> 00:11:32.384
and you're operating
with you've got

00:11:32.384 --> 00:11:34.050
a scalpel in one hand
and the other hand

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:36.110
you're playing Angry
Birds or something.

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:37.710
That's what actively disengaged.

00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:39.849
So that's about a
third of the workforce.

00:11:39.849 --> 00:11:42.140
And if you think about the
experiences you have in life

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:45.780
with people who you know who
work at other places, people

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:48.300
you experience in your daily
life at the coffee shop

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:51.372
or at the insurance
agency, it show.

00:11:51.372 --> 00:11:53.080
We all have these
experiences with people

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:55.070
where they are clearly
not interested in what

00:11:55.070 --> 00:11:56.240
they're doing.

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:57.920
Now I know from
my own experience,

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:02.370
I've had a fair number of
lousy, lousy jobs in my life.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:04.970
I've done telemarketing,
I've been a waiter.

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:06.710
Then all sorts of odd
job just to make it

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:08.210
through college and whatnot.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:12.370
And I know that some of
those jobs, I was engaged.

00:12:12.370 --> 00:12:14.440
Not all of them, but
some of them I were.

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:17.060
And it depended on
who I was working with

00:12:17.060 --> 00:12:19.280
and who I was working for.

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:22.980
So I look at this number as
an indictment of management.

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:24.380
As a discipline.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:26.630
That this means there's
something fundamentally broken

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:29.590
about the basic notion
of how managers function

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:31.585
and how they evaluate
their own work.

00:12:31.585 --> 00:12:32.960
And so, I was
interested in going

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:35.750
to work at WordPress.com
for a bunch of reasons.

00:12:35.750 --> 00:12:39.340
First, it was a culture
that had no managers.

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:42.390
Up until the point I was
hired, there was no such thing.

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:45.040
And they were experimenting
with introducing

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:46.990
a layer of management.

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:49.350
Which is an unusual
situation to observe,

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:51.020
much less participate in.

00:12:51.020 --> 00:12:53.750
And second, having had previous
experience as a manager,

00:12:53.750 --> 00:12:55.170
most of my career
at Microsoft was

00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:57.810
spent as a team
leader kind of guy.

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:00.040
I was interested
to see what I could

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.520
do to bring the good parts of
what good managers do and see

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:06.140
if I could possibly use
that in a valuable way

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:07.177
inside the culture.

00:13:07.177 --> 00:13:08.510
So that's the story of the book.

00:13:08.510 --> 00:13:11.240
The book follows
my year of trying

00:13:11.240 --> 00:13:14.490
to hey, do any of these things
that I have in my toolkit

00:13:14.490 --> 00:13:15.790
actually matter anymore?

00:13:15.790 --> 00:13:16.949
Do they work?

00:13:16.949 --> 00:13:19.240
And the book follows me
experimenting and trying things

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:20.990
out and failing in many cases.

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:22.280
Succeeding in others.

00:13:22.280 --> 00:13:24.890
And eventually arriving
at some conclusions about

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:29.800
how the function of management
in these nontraditional more

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:32.960
employee centered environments.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:35.880
There's good reasons why
management is so flawed.

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:38.610
The primary one being that
the origins of management

00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:41.820
as a profession come
from the industrial age.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.190
And it was the robber baron
era of the industrial age that

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:48.000
funded most of the major
business schools, at least

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.030
in America.

00:13:49.030 --> 00:13:51.130
Not all of them,
but many of them.

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:54.619
Vanderbilt, the Oil
Barons, Rockefeller, these

00:13:54.619 --> 00:13:57.160
are the people that funded most
of the major business schools

00:13:57.160 --> 00:13:58.240
that we have.

00:13:58.240 --> 00:14:03.670
And those industries,
banking, oil, railroads, most

00:14:03.670 --> 00:14:06.780
of the work that needed to be
done was industrial age work.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:10.070
So the central point of what
was thought to be creative work

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:11.920
was done by management.

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:14.530
So it's no surprise the people
who come from MBA schools

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:16.450
are largely trained
at executives

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:18.580
are the most important
and central visionary

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:21.597
force in any organization.

00:14:21.597 --> 00:14:23.680
And that may be true if
you're managing people who

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:28.350
are doing repetitive work.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:31.100
Who are in a factory
and they are basically

00:14:31.100 --> 00:14:33.310
applying Taylor's time
and motion studies

00:14:33.310 --> 00:14:35.760
to how many widgets they can
make per minute or per hour.

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:37.760
You could argue that maybe
that stuff make sense

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.340
there, but as we have moved
into this knowledge age

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:43.150
where most people
are making things,

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:46.220
could be writing code, or
designing software, or writing

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:48.700
blog posts, or it could
be making documents,

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:51.300
or spreadsheets, but when
people are making things,

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:54.590
that centricity on executives
I think is dubious.

00:14:54.590 --> 00:14:57.650
That's rarely where the most
important visionary work

00:14:57.650 --> 00:14:58.895
is going to happen anymore.

00:14:58.895 --> 00:15:01.270
And there's a lot of evidence
that support for the theory

00:15:01.270 --> 00:15:04.420
that innovation and progress
always happens on the margins,

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:07.150
it happens on the people
who have the least at stake.

00:15:07.150 --> 00:15:09.930
So this notion that we've
inherited about what managers

00:15:09.930 --> 00:15:12.630
do and how they work
I think is flawed.

00:15:12.630 --> 00:15:14.037
And I wanted to
investigate that.

00:15:14.037 --> 00:15:16.620
The other interesting question,
it's probably the most popular

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:19.080
thing that WordPress.com
and Automatic

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:20.700
is the name of the
company that runs

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:23.990
WordPress.com. is this
notion of remote work.

00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:27.220
It's the question that
comes up the most.

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:30.930
Right now, about
20% of all people

00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:33.310
who work in professional
jobs work remotely.

00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:34.940
And that number's been climbing.

00:15:34.940 --> 00:15:36.780
And will probably
continue to climb.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:39.160
So right now it's about 1 in 5.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:42.800
And if you consider
the number of companies

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:45.100
that have liberal
remote work policies,

00:15:45.100 --> 00:15:47.350
where you're allowed to work
from home one day a week.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:50.080
Or a few days a month,
the number's even larger.

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:51.880
And I think as tools
get better and better

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:56.690
and there's more things where
the work is done primarily

00:15:56.690 --> 00:16:00.230
through computers, I think this
number will continue to climb.

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:01.857
There's lots of
workplaces that I've

00:16:01.857 --> 00:16:03.190
been talking about the book now.

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:05.360
It's been out for just a few
weeks, but I'm on book tour

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:07.443
right now so I got to lots
of places like you guys

00:16:07.443 --> 00:16:08.652
and I talk about in the book.

00:16:08.652 --> 00:16:10.942
And there's lots of companies
who are just very freaked

00:16:10.942 --> 00:16:12.260
out by this remote work notion.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:14.970
And I am actually not a
super zealot about it.

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:16.820
I don't think everyone
should work remotely.

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:18.195
But I think the
questions that it

00:16:18.195 --> 00:16:20.600
raises are really good
about why should you

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:22.220
care about where people are.

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:24.390
You should care about
how productive they are.

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:29.700
And if they can be productive
on a jeep on safari in Africa

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:33.000
that happens to have good Wi-Fi,
and the code they check in

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.430
and the writing they do,
whatever their job is good,

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:36.940
why should you care?

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:39.740
If their coworkers are happy
with the collaboration that's

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:41.609
going on, why does it matter?

00:16:41.609 --> 00:16:43.150
So a lot of these
places where people

00:16:43.150 --> 00:16:47.490
get these very defensive
responses about remote work,

00:16:47.490 --> 00:16:50.300
I usually ask them
a simple question.

00:16:50.300 --> 00:16:54.940
What percentage of
your time in an office

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:57.360
is spent working with
your coworkers purely

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:00.480
through a computer?

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:03.040
And they think about
it and it's high.

00:17:03.040 --> 00:17:04.890
50%, 60%.

00:17:04.890 --> 00:17:06.530
It's really high.

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:10.849
And I'm thinking email, anything
you do through a web browser.

00:17:10.849 --> 00:17:15.260
Could be a chatroom, it could
be a message board, Skype,

00:17:15.260 --> 00:17:16.972
or even on the telephone,
which is really

00:17:16.972 --> 00:17:19.180
one of the first kinds of
remote work we've ever had.

00:17:19.180 --> 00:17:20.220
It's high.

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:22.675
So if your work is mostly
mediated through a computer,

00:17:22.675 --> 00:17:25.240
your location is irrelevant.

00:17:25.240 --> 00:17:26.609
Does not matter.

00:17:26.609 --> 00:17:28.860
For the 30% or 40% of the
time that you actually

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:31.590
need to be at a whiteboard
together, or at a meeting

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:32.694
together, fine.

00:17:32.694 --> 00:17:34.110
But for the majority
of your time,

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:36.568
if it's spent through computers,
which most workplaces are.

00:17:36.568 --> 00:17:38.490
This number should not
be that surprising.

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:40.674
You're already
doing remote work.

00:17:40.674 --> 00:17:42.590
If you've ever had the
experience where you're

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:45.290
in a conference room where
one person is talking

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:46.750
and the other 12
people in the room

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:50.560
are staring at their laptop,
who here has had that happen?

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:51.580
Most of you, right.

00:17:51.580 --> 00:17:53.320
What is going on there?

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:56.830
You have one person talking,
12 people on their laptops

00:17:56.830 --> 00:18:00.470
doing something else, that
could be entirely done remotely.

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:02.940
Anyway, so that's the other
big question that comes up.

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:05.670
20% that number's on the rise.

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:07.430
So I had all of these
questions coming

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:09.230
in to taking on this project.

00:18:09.230 --> 00:18:13.949
One was personal about my
own figuring out my relevance

00:18:13.949 --> 00:18:15.490
as an expert and
wanting to challenge

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:18.884
myself to see how
much I practiced.

00:18:18.884 --> 00:18:21.050
Then there's all these other
questions that come up.

00:18:21.050 --> 00:18:22.760
What other work
conventions do we

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:28.800
have today, even in successful
workplaces, that make no sense

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:31.770
or have no data to support them?

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:33.697
Working 9:00 to 5:00 is one.

00:18:33.697 --> 00:18:36.030
I have yet to see a study
that says working 9:00 to 5:00

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:37.721
makes you more productive.

00:18:37.721 --> 00:18:39.720
There's lots of evidence
to say that it doesn't.

00:18:39.720 --> 00:18:41.261
Because usually that
means a commute.

00:18:41.261 --> 00:18:44.240
So that means 35 minutes,
40 minutes, an hour a day

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:47.150
spent in frustration.

00:18:47.150 --> 00:18:51.900
Spent sacrificing time
just to get to a place.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:53.870
Where you're going
to stare at a screen.

00:18:53.870 --> 00:18:55.170
I wanted to ask that question.

00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:57.550
Then there are other ones
too about dress codes.

00:18:57.550 --> 00:18:59.600
I'm talking to you guys
in the software industry

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:01.620
and I can tell by looking at
you, you guys are well dressed,

00:19:01.620 --> 00:19:03.245
but we're in the
software industry here

00:19:03.245 --> 00:19:06.010
and dress code is not really
an important problem anymore.

00:19:06.010 --> 00:19:07.960
For most the working
world, that's not true.

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:09.790
Dress codes are
still something that

00:19:09.790 --> 00:19:12.190
is mandated in most workplaces.

00:19:12.190 --> 00:19:13.565
Then other things
like hierarchy,

00:19:13.565 --> 00:19:15.755
and meetings, this
question about email,

00:19:15.755 --> 00:19:18.130
I had all these big questions
I wanted to try and answer.

00:19:18.130 --> 00:19:20.150
So I'm going to give you
some of those answers

00:19:20.150 --> 00:19:23.190
and then I'll open the
floor for questions.

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:27.850
So this picture is my
team when I was hired.

00:19:27.850 --> 00:19:31.044
So this was taken in
September of 2010.

00:19:31.044 --> 00:19:32.710
And when I was hired,
my team was small.

00:19:32.710 --> 00:19:35.934
We had three developers and
we were all in the same place.

00:19:35.934 --> 00:19:38.350
What's interesting, of course,
we're all in the same place

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:39.266
and what are we doing?

00:19:39.266 --> 00:19:40.308
We're staring at screens.

00:19:40.308 --> 00:19:41.807
And on these screens,
we're actually

00:19:41.807 --> 00:19:42.910
chatting with each other.

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:44.254
This was a common occurrence.

00:19:44.254 --> 00:19:46.420
I'm sure it's been a common
occurrence for you guys,

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:47.052
as well.

00:19:47.052 --> 00:19:48.760
What's unusual about
this photo, and what

00:19:48.760 --> 00:19:50.426
you can't tell from
the photo is that it

00:19:50.426 --> 00:19:52.930
looks like we're in some
kind of dumpy apartment

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:54.165
with bad lighting.

00:19:54.165 --> 00:19:56.290
We were not in a dumpy
apartment with bad lighting.

00:19:56.290 --> 00:19:59.950
We were in a dumpy hotel room,
I'm sorry dumpy hotel lobby

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:00.980
with bad lighting.

00:20:00.980 --> 00:20:02.850
And we happen to
be Athens, Greece.

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:05.440
The reason why we were in
Athens, Greece is very simple.

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:07.560
The people in this
room, all these guys who

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:10.380
worked on my team were all from
different parts of the world.

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:12.470
So Mike Adams on the
left was from California,

00:20:12.470 --> 00:20:14.830
Andy Peatling in the
middle was from Ireland,

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:18.000
and Beau Lebens on the
right was from Australia.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.569
And the company
supported the notion

00:20:19.569 --> 00:20:21.610
that periodically, every
team should get together

00:20:21.610 --> 00:20:24.730
to be face to face to capture
all the intangibles you can't

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:25.930
get remotely.

00:20:25.930 --> 00:20:27.610
So even for a
company that's 100%

00:20:27.610 --> 00:20:30.860
distributed and is a poster
child for remote work,

00:20:30.860 --> 00:20:33.190
there's this believe from
the founders of the company,

00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:36.120
periodically you need to refresh
all these little things you

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:38.160
get only when you're together.

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:39.907
Having the team
newly formed, no one

00:20:39.907 --> 00:20:41.490
had done one of these
meet-ups before,

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:44.060
so we decide to go
and try to figure out

00:20:44.060 --> 00:20:45.600
how these things
would even work.

00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:47.700
And this is that photo.

00:20:52.910 --> 00:20:55.369
Now the challenge I had with
this team of developers,

00:20:55.369 --> 00:20:56.785
so I'm actually
not a developer, I

00:20:56.785 --> 00:20:58.660
have a background
in Computer Science,

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:00.900
I knew halfway through my
Computer Science degree

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:02.560
that I would never
be a good developer.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:04.630
So I tried to find
something else to do.

00:21:04.630 --> 00:21:07.160
I learned about UI design
and Project Management

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:10.120
and that's allowed me to
be a manager at Microsoft.

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:11.840
I had enough of a
technical background

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:14.010
to collaborate and
evaluate developers,

00:21:14.010 --> 00:21:15.680
but I've never really been one.

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:18.840
So my role on the team, I
didn't write a line of code.

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:22.404
My job instead was that a
meta-job of figuring out

00:21:22.404 --> 00:21:24.570
what is a lead need in the
structure of this company

00:21:24.570 --> 00:21:26.740
and if I could figure
out how to do that,

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:29.435
can I teach other lead at the
company to do the same thing?

00:21:29.435 --> 00:21:31.310
Now this was a huge challenge.

00:21:31.310 --> 00:21:32.790
This was a terrifying challenge.

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:35.980
How do I figure out how a
team should work and add

00:21:35.980 --> 00:21:37.000
some kind of structure?

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:38.690
Because that's what a team is.

00:21:38.690 --> 00:21:42.010
Into a young, very
non-corporate, chaotic,

00:21:42.010 --> 00:21:45.240
developer-centric,
autonomous culture.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:47.880
What is my approach going to be?

00:21:47.880 --> 00:21:49.560
What tricks am I
going to employ?

00:21:49.560 --> 00:21:50.930
What tactics?

00:21:50.930 --> 00:21:53.630
Most of management
literature is just

00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:55.307
methodologies
where you just tell

00:21:55.307 --> 00:21:57.390
people what to do and put
boxes around everything.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:21:58.450
And I knew none of
that stuff would work.

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:00.230
I didn't like any of
that stuff anyway.

00:22:00.230 --> 00:22:02.090
But I knew none
of it would work.

00:22:02.090 --> 00:22:04.210
So I thought really
hard about this

00:22:04.210 --> 00:22:07.730
before I got hired to come up
with some kind of playbook.

00:22:07.730 --> 00:22:15.070
And the answer that I came up
with was embarrassingly simple.

00:22:15.070 --> 00:22:18.560
That I needed to provide
clarity and trust.

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:19.405
Clarity and trust.

00:22:22.492 --> 00:22:24.950
It seems underwhelming that
this was my grand strategy just

00:22:24.950 --> 00:22:25.970
these two things.

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:29.290
But I was convinced that part
of why that 70% engagement

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:31.780
number in the general
workplace is so low

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:35.130
is because managers failed
to provide these two things.

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:37.510
They failed to earn the
trust of their employees,

00:22:37.510 --> 00:22:39.444
they failed to trust
their employees as well,

00:22:39.444 --> 00:22:40.860
and they failed
to provide clarity

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:44.450
about why certain
decisions are made.

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:46.396
So this is my playbook
in my approach.

00:22:46.396 --> 00:22:48.270
And when I was first
hired, the first thing I

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:50.160
did as a lead was nothing.

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:51.980
I decided that in
order to earn trust,

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:54.614
I had to be patient
and just listen.

00:22:54.614 --> 00:22:56.780
So for the first few weeks
that we worked as a team,

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:57.988
I didn't really do very much.

00:22:57.988 --> 00:23:00.360
I was basically the scribe.

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:02.460
I was a scribe.

00:23:02.460 --> 00:23:05.750
It was the only tool I
could use to earn trust.

00:23:05.750 --> 00:23:08.410
We'd have a conversation
in IRC or on Skype

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:11.980
and I'd write up a summary and
I'd post it on our team blog.

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:14.200
And I'd show that I
reflected what I heard,

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:15.225
I distilled it down.

00:23:15.225 --> 00:23:17.804
And little by little, I
showed that I was not a moron

00:23:17.804 --> 00:23:19.220
and that I'd been
paying attention

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:22.070
and I could think well.

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:25.719
As management goes, that's
a good curve to get over.

00:23:25.719 --> 00:23:27.510
I'm sure you've had
managers at your career

00:23:27.510 --> 00:23:29.507
where they didn't
quite meet those bars.

00:23:29.507 --> 00:23:31.090
And then little by
little, I converted

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:32.714
from being the scribe,
to being someone

00:23:32.714 --> 00:23:34.750
who initiated conversations.

00:23:34.750 --> 00:23:36.560
And then initiated
how we make decisions.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:39.326
And then eventually,
I tried to work my way

00:23:39.326 --> 00:23:41.200
to having enough trust
that I was effectively

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:42.630
the leader of the team.

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:45.045
And help decide the
direction and decisions

00:23:45.045 --> 00:23:46.670
and which things we
would do or not do.

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:53.270
The technology here,
this is the thing

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:55.520
that people usually
most want to know.

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:57.450
Is how did we actually work.

00:23:57.450 --> 00:23:58.400
What was a day like?

00:23:58.400 --> 00:23:59.280
What was a week like?

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:02.020
How did you get around email?

00:24:02.020 --> 00:24:03.770
And there were
three simple tools

00:24:03.770 --> 00:24:06.530
that we use for most
of our communication.

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:12.044
IRC, Internet Relay Chat,
ancient program from like 1985.

00:24:12.044 --> 00:24:13.710
Very popular in open
source communities,

00:24:13.710 --> 00:24:15.500
which is why WordPress used it.

00:24:15.500 --> 00:24:16.270
Two is Skype.

00:24:16.270 --> 00:24:18.690
And three was blogs.

00:24:18.690 --> 00:24:20.640
Also not a surprise,
given that WordPress.com

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:22.065
is a blogging company.

00:24:22.065 --> 00:24:23.690
Of course you're
going to use the thing

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:25.190
that you think
everyone should use.

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:26.273
Those are the three tools.

00:24:26.273 --> 00:24:29.030
So 90% of our communication,
my communication

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:33.260
with the team and the company
went through these three tools.

00:24:33.260 --> 00:24:36.270
IRC, which is in the photo
all the way in the left

00:24:36.270 --> 00:24:38.110
is effectively the hallway.

00:24:38.110 --> 00:24:41.860
That's how I tried
to map my outsider

00:24:41.860 --> 00:24:43.030
experience at WordPress.

00:24:43.030 --> 00:24:44.640
It's the hallway.

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:46.760
It's where you go to
interact with people

00:24:46.760 --> 00:24:48.310
you wouldn't normally meet.

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:49.780
The whole company's
usually there.

00:24:49.780 --> 00:24:50.930
Whoever's working.

00:24:50.930 --> 00:24:53.330
You can go in there and talk
to anyone about anything.

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:54.495
If you have a
question or some bug

00:24:54.495 --> 00:24:55.930
you're trying to
fix or something,

00:24:55.930 --> 00:24:58.021
you're trying to track
down, you go in there

00:24:58.021 --> 00:25:00.270
and you ask a question and
someone invariably be, hey,

00:25:00.270 --> 00:25:01.990
yeah sure I'll help you
take a look at that.

00:25:01.990 --> 00:25:04.630
It's also where you go to have
social chats where something's

00:25:04.630 --> 00:25:06.610
going on in the news,
you can go in there

00:25:06.610 --> 00:25:07.710
and have a conversation.

00:25:07.710 --> 00:25:08.900
It's the hallway.

00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:11.070
That's where the
serendipity happens.

00:25:11.070 --> 00:25:13.220
And that's where
meetings often happened,

00:25:13.220 --> 00:25:15.650
as much as there were
meetings, which there were not

00:25:15.650 --> 00:25:16.710
very many of them.

00:25:16.710 --> 00:25:18.990
Skype was the equivalent
to one on one conversations

00:25:18.990 --> 00:25:19.974
and communication.

00:25:19.974 --> 00:25:22.140
So all the interactions,
or most of the interactions

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:25.010
I had with my team,
would often be in Skype.

00:25:25.010 --> 00:25:26.520
Certainly, any
conversation I have

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:29.400
with someone who's on my team
where it was manager employee

00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:32.270
conversation, it was about
performance, or critique,

00:25:32.270 --> 00:25:34.910
or feedback, that'd
be done in Skype.

00:25:34.910 --> 00:25:39.040
And then blogs was
the dominant medium

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:41.384
for all team interaction.

00:25:41.384 --> 00:25:44.050
So all the stuff that often goes
on an email, where there's long

00:25:44.050 --> 00:25:45.840
discussion threads
about should we

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:47.550
design it this way or that way?

00:25:47.550 --> 00:25:48.480
What about this?

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:50.780
Most of that stuff
was done on blogs.

00:25:50.780 --> 00:25:52.340
Instead of being
in an email thread,

00:25:52.340 --> 00:25:55.380
it would be in a comment thread.

00:25:55.380 --> 00:26:00.280
The upside of this was that
all this stuff, certainly

00:26:00.280 --> 00:26:03.415
IRC and the blogs, are visible.

00:26:03.415 --> 00:26:04.871
It's transparent.

00:26:04.871 --> 00:26:06.620
So anyone at the company
could go and read

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:07.900
any of these things.

00:26:07.900 --> 00:26:11.470
Unlike email, it's all
searchable and archival.

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:12.429
Stuff lives on forever.

00:26:12.429 --> 00:26:14.178
[INAUDIBLE] you don't
have to do anything.

00:26:14.178 --> 00:26:15.800
You get all of that for free.

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:18.610
The downside was that
all the stuff is public.

00:26:18.610 --> 00:26:20.580
All the stuff is
visible to everybody.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:22.020
So I had some
challenges, and some

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:24.480
of the critique that I have
with the culture of the company

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:34.280
was that I found it was
hard to get truly, brutally

00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:36.142
honest critiques of work.

00:26:36.142 --> 00:26:37.600
Because people did
not want to look

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:40.050
mean in front of
the whole company.

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:41.850
It was also hard for
people, in some cases,

00:26:41.850 --> 00:26:45.276
to be truly expressive
of their opinions

00:26:45.276 --> 00:26:47.400
because they knew this
stuff would live on forever.

00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:49.170
And I could talk
more about how I

00:26:49.170 --> 00:26:52.270
tried, at least on my own team,
to overcome those challenges.

00:26:52.270 --> 00:26:55.400
Anyway, technologically
speaking, this is the story.

00:26:55.400 --> 00:26:57.395
This explains the
remote work process,

00:26:57.395 --> 00:27:00.380
it explains how we got
away with not using email.

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:03.075
And it should be
maybe a mild surprise,

00:27:03.075 --> 00:27:07.100
these are all free tools.

00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:08.530
There's no magic here.

00:27:08.530 --> 00:27:11.140
It's like there was some special
video conferencing software

00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:12.800
that they used or invented.

00:27:12.800 --> 00:27:16.810
These are all cheap
and fairly old tools.

00:27:16.810 --> 00:27:20.940
Which I think is incredibly
telling about many answers

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:24.150
to questions about why certain
workplaces function and why

00:27:24.150 --> 00:27:25.790
certain workplaces don't.

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:27.550
That it's not about
the management method,

00:27:27.550 --> 00:27:29.160
it's not about the technology.

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:30.970
It's about the culture.

00:27:30.970 --> 00:27:33.370
The culture being
the basic units

00:27:33.370 --> 00:27:35.790
of interactions and
assumptions in protocols

00:27:35.790 --> 00:27:38.010
that people have
naturally about how

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:39.770
they interact with each other.

00:27:39.770 --> 00:27:42.950
So it turned out that at
WordPress.com, I was shocked.

00:27:42.950 --> 00:27:49.120
That one of the biggest shocks
I had was everybody writes well.

00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:51.269
Everybody writes well.

00:27:51.269 --> 00:27:51.935
It was shocking.

00:27:51.935 --> 00:27:52.890
It was mind-blowing.

00:27:56.140 --> 00:27:58.300
I never thought that
would be a secret.

00:27:58.300 --> 00:28:01.310
Because every company in the
world has the same rhetoric.

00:28:01.310 --> 00:28:04.350
We are excellent communicators.

00:28:04.350 --> 00:28:08.130
We write clearly and
which, most people don't.

00:28:08.130 --> 00:28:10.060
But that explains why
there was so little

00:28:10.060 --> 00:28:12.930
need for structure, why these
tools could be so lightweight.

00:28:12.930 --> 00:28:16.720
Because the tools can
never do the hard parts.

00:28:16.720 --> 00:28:19.934
Of having people have high
reading comprehension.

00:28:19.934 --> 00:28:21.850
Or people who are willing
to write generously,

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:23.380
and carefully, and thoughtfully.

00:28:25.930 --> 00:28:27.610
Every team had its own blog.

00:28:27.610 --> 00:28:30.730
There's a special theme,
WordPress theme that they use

00:28:30.730 --> 00:28:33.770
called P2, which solves
many the annoyances

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:35.930
of blogs in terms of teamwork.

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:39.720
So the P2 theme which is a
publicly available open source

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:41.570
theme, works sort
of like Twitter.

00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:45.880
You go to the P2 or the team
blog, there's a box at the top,

00:28:45.880 --> 00:28:48.130
you can type it whatever
it is you're working on

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:49.390
and you hit post.

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:53.930
So there's no dashboard or any
other admin UI to deal with.

00:28:53.930 --> 00:28:56.640
And that allows for very quick,
very fast, very lightweight

00:28:56.640 --> 00:28:59.580
updating and posting of things.

00:28:59.580 --> 00:29:01.320
And also they were
very personalized.

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:03.160
So once the teams
were formed, there

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:05.550
was this question of whether
teams would work at all.

00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:08.890
I think the P2 is the fact
that every team had one.

00:29:08.890 --> 00:29:11.770
Enabled some kinds of
tribalism to start.

00:29:11.770 --> 00:29:14.010
Where teams would
start to embellish,

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.500
we're all designers
and developers,

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:19.570
they'd start to embellish
their team blogs.

00:29:19.570 --> 00:29:24.170
And that helped team cultures
to develop on their own.

00:29:24.170 --> 00:29:27.730
So I'm going to wrap up and
open the floor for questions

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:29.900
in just a second.

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:32.810
The story about my
experience there, I think

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:37.620
is important not because I
advocate people copy everything

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:42.330
that WordPress.com does, but
the example and the questions

00:29:42.330 --> 00:29:45.686
that they ask I think
are very important.

00:29:45.686 --> 00:29:47.060
About questioning
the assumptions

00:29:47.060 --> 00:29:49.190
we have about how work is done.

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:54.910
And also forcing the
responsibility or making

00:29:54.910 --> 00:29:58.940
visible the responsibility
that managers and executives

00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:02.460
have to experiment
and be open to trying

00:30:02.460 --> 00:30:05.520
different ways of working.

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:07.830
To be open and try
different ways of working.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:09.985
Remote work just being
one example of that.

00:30:09.985 --> 00:30:12.730
Any executive who
tells me that they

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:15.294
have a good performing
employee who said,

00:30:15.294 --> 00:30:17.710
I want to try to work remotely
and they say, I would never

00:30:17.710 --> 00:30:19.400
let them do that, I
think is an idiot.

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:20.980
I think they're a fool.

00:30:20.980 --> 00:30:22.850
What do they have to
lose by experimenting

00:30:22.850 --> 00:30:25.900
and let someone try
working remotely?

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:28.360
If they can actually work
remotely and perform just

00:30:28.360 --> 00:30:31.290
as well, that's an advantage.

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:34.360
You now have an employee
that is really happy doing

00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:36.390
the same amount of
work and will continue

00:30:36.390 --> 00:30:39.270
looking for ways to
work better and smarter.

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:42.910
Which is what every executive
and manager should want.

00:30:42.910 --> 00:30:44.650
And maybe it's not
working remotely.

00:30:44.650 --> 00:30:48.200
Maybe it's trying to work
with less email centricity.

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:51.260
Or maybe it's trying to work
where a different tool was used

00:30:51.260 --> 00:30:53.950
to communicate or to manage
progress or whatever.

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:56.740
There's so much resistance
to even experimentation

00:30:56.740 --> 00:30:57.240
and trying.

00:30:57.240 --> 00:30:59.550
And I think that's
the fundamental lesson

00:30:59.550 --> 00:31:01.550
I hope people get
from reading the book

00:31:01.550 --> 00:31:03.880
and hearing the story
of me experimenting.

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:08.150
And them experimented but having
me come in as an employee.

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:10.270
These numbers I think
are going to get worse

00:31:10.270 --> 00:31:12.000
in terms of employee engagement.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:13.750
I also think the numbers
of remote workers

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:14.660
is going to go up.

00:31:14.660 --> 00:31:17.220
And those two trends
along makes WordPress.com

00:31:17.220 --> 00:31:22.600
an interesting example
that I hope people study.

00:31:22.600 --> 00:31:23.870
So that's my talk.

00:31:23.870 --> 00:31:26.648
Thank you for listening so far.

00:31:26.648 --> 00:31:30.842
[APPLAUSE]

