SCOTT BERKUN: Thank
you, Mr. First Clap guy.

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:35.480
It's an important role.

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:37.021
So I'll open the
floor for questions.

00:31:37.021 --> 00:31:37.980
You guys came here.

00:31:37.980 --> 00:31:40.000
I am an open book, literally.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.010
So I will answer any
question that you're

00:31:42.010 --> 00:31:43.140
brave enough to ask.

00:31:43.140 --> 00:31:44.310
Yeah?

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:46.055
AUDIENCE: So was it
your experience that

00:31:46.055 --> 00:31:47.790
with this
nontraditional workplace

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:52.010
that 100% of your employees
were engaged and productive?

00:31:52.010 --> 00:31:55.820
And if not, how did
you deal with that?

00:31:55.820 --> 00:31:58.350
SCOTT BERKUN: I think that
engagement was very high there.

00:31:58.350 --> 00:32:01.020
I couldn't give you a
number because it wasn't

00:32:01.020 --> 00:32:04.210
the kind of place that did
employee surveys and polls

00:32:04.210 --> 00:32:05.270
and whatnot.

00:32:05.270 --> 00:32:07.900
But certainly, my
team was very engaged.

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:11.520
I had a really solid team.

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:14.130
The company because of
its open source roots

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:16.005
and because of how
they hire, engagement

00:32:16.005 --> 00:32:16.880
is a different story.

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:18.338
So I should tell
you how they hire.

00:32:18.338 --> 00:32:19.580
Because it's very unusual.

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:22.130
And really clever.

00:32:22.130 --> 00:32:24.280
They don't do interviews.

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:28.230
Instead, and this will
blow your mind, it's crazy.

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:31.510
They hire you by trial.

00:32:31.510 --> 00:32:34.550
So if you make it
through referrals

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:37.440
and they decide that they
want to possibly consider

00:32:37.440 --> 00:32:40.380
hiring you, you are
given an actual project

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:41.860
that needs to be done.

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:43.900
And hey, here you go.

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:44.500
Go do it.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:48.290
Here's access to some of our IRC
chatrooms, some of our blogs,

00:32:48.290 --> 00:32:49.550
some of our code base.

00:32:49.550 --> 00:32:51.050
You have access, go.

00:32:51.050 --> 00:32:55.120
We'll pay you a little bit
of money, go build the thing.

00:32:55.120 --> 00:33:00.430
And that's a radical idea in
the tech community, the business

00:33:00.430 --> 00:33:01.652
community, it's radical.

00:33:01.652 --> 00:33:03.360
Oh, it's too expensive,
it's too painful.

00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:06.370
Then you think about how you
hire people in your own life.

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:10.660
Like if you were having a
wedding and you wanted a cake,

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:13.110
you wouldn't go to the
bake and go, why don't you

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:16.400
tell me about your strengths
and weaknesses as a baker?

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:18.800
Tell me about a baking
project that went wrong

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:20.530
and what you've learned from it.

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:22.390
Like you would
never, ever do that.

00:33:22.390 --> 00:33:24.155
You'd say, make me a cake.

00:33:24.155 --> 00:33:26.750
I'm hiring you to make
cakes, make me a cake.

00:33:26.750 --> 00:33:28.150
So they do the same thing.

00:33:28.150 --> 00:33:32.350
And because they are a tech
company, most of the employees

00:33:32.350 --> 00:33:34.750
are either designers,
or developers,

00:33:34.750 --> 00:33:37.190
or writers, people
who make stuff.

00:33:37.190 --> 00:33:39.300
They say, OK, go make stuff.

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:43.860
And that process eliminates
many of the challenges

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:45.480
that most workplaces do.

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:48.220
Because a lot of the
trial projects fail.

00:33:48.220 --> 00:33:50.190
Some people are not
willing to put in the time.

00:33:50.190 --> 00:33:53.890
They already have a job, they
don't want to do more work.

00:33:53.890 --> 00:33:56.391
To do a trial project, and trial
projects are usually small.

00:33:56.391 --> 00:33:58.223
But it's going to take
a couple of weekends,

00:33:58.223 --> 00:33:59.550
it's going to take some time.

00:33:59.550 --> 00:34:01.600
A lot of people
who say they want

00:34:01.600 --> 00:34:04.990
to work there, they just
give up on the trial.

00:34:04.990 --> 00:34:06.440
So that's about engagement.

00:34:06.440 --> 00:34:09.679
How interested really
are you in WordPress?

00:34:09.679 --> 00:34:11.860
How interested are you
really in blogging?

00:34:11.860 --> 00:34:14.130
And maybe you think
you are because you've

00:34:14.130 --> 00:34:16.889
heard about remote work or some
other attribute of the company,

00:34:16.889 --> 00:34:19.460
but really, here's a project.

00:34:19.460 --> 00:34:21.159
And that project,
that trial project

00:34:21.159 --> 00:34:23.480
also helps with filtering
people out there

00:34:23.480 --> 00:34:26.300
who are not suited
to be remote workers.

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:28.429
Trial projects,
there is no schedule.

00:34:28.429 --> 00:34:31.560
No one tells you how much of
your trial to get done today.

00:34:31.560 --> 00:34:33.719
Which is the same way
the culture works.

00:34:33.719 --> 00:34:36.219
Even though we have teams
now, and I was a lead,

00:34:36.219 --> 00:34:38.461
it's a very, very
hands-off culture.

00:34:38.461 --> 00:34:38.960
It's

00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:42.170
Assumed that because you
are a developer or designer,

00:34:42.170 --> 00:34:44.100
you know how to
manage your time.

00:34:44.100 --> 00:34:46.210
You know how to get stuff done.

00:34:46.210 --> 00:34:49.179
You have a basic ability
to time management.

00:34:49.179 --> 00:34:50.730
So people who fail
the trial project

00:34:50.730 --> 00:34:53.230
are probably people who wouldn't
make good employees anyway.

00:34:56.133 --> 00:34:56.799
Other questions?

00:35:04.050 --> 00:35:06.050
AUDIENCE: Perhaps you
were a little too generous

00:35:06.050 --> 00:35:09.825
to the existing
management paradigm.

00:35:09.825 --> 00:35:12.770
I mean if you look at the
auto companies that do well,

00:35:12.770 --> 00:35:15.250
they're places like
the Japanese ones which

00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:18.490
get 2000 pieces of advice
from the floor each year,

00:35:18.490 --> 00:35:20.276
and through a
continuous improvement,

00:35:20.276 --> 00:35:21.275
get a better engagement.

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:26.089
Your comments?

00:35:26.089 --> 00:35:26.880
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure.

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:37.640
I think engagement is
largely about respect.

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:39.440
And there's lots
of workplaces where

00:35:39.440 --> 00:35:41.750
employees know
they're not respected.

00:35:41.750 --> 00:35:45.014
It's a very basic emotional
anthropological principle.

00:35:45.014 --> 00:35:47.430
I don't think you need any
sort of fancy management method

00:35:47.430 --> 00:35:48.506
to know that.

00:35:48.506 --> 00:35:50.130
It's about treating
people like people.

00:35:50.130 --> 00:35:51.920
And when people are
treated like people

00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:53.220
they tend to behave better.

00:35:53.220 --> 00:35:56.690
Because they feel better
about how meaningful the work

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:58.610
they're doing is.

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:01.010
So you could look
at Toyota, which

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:03.910
has a history of implementing
a lot of these methods

00:36:03.910 --> 00:36:08.920
that the US auto companies have
been trying to emulate or copy

00:36:08.920 --> 00:36:12.801
or whatnot, but we're
prone to copying the method

00:36:12.801 --> 00:36:14.300
and believing that
there's something

00:36:14.300 --> 00:36:15.950
magical in the techniques.

00:36:15.950 --> 00:36:18.190
It's a very logical
view of the world.

00:36:18.190 --> 00:36:20.530
But there's just something
natural and human

00:36:20.530 --> 00:36:23.866
about being willing
to treat people well.

00:36:23.866 --> 00:36:25.240
And that's part
of the principles

00:36:25.240 --> 00:36:29.550
that I learned at
WordPress.com about not just

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:32.724
the platitude of it, but
you're hired, you're smart,

00:36:32.724 --> 00:36:33.390
you're an adult.

00:36:33.390 --> 00:36:35.490
Why would we treat
you in a way that

00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:37.220
pretended like you're a child?

00:36:37.220 --> 00:36:39.420
Which is how most
workplaces operate.

00:36:39.420 --> 00:36:40.890
Most restrictions
that workplaces

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:42.500
have are very parental.

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:44.250
Oh, that'd be bad for
you if you did that,

00:36:44.250 --> 00:36:45.510
so we're not going
to let you do that.

00:36:45.510 --> 00:36:47.160
And that's the
logic that they use.

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:48.820
And we're executives
and managers,

00:36:48.820 --> 00:36:51.750
so therefore, we
should be parenting.

00:36:51.750 --> 00:36:52.680
That's our job.

00:36:52.680 --> 00:36:56.526
If we are not creating rules and
structures, what are we doing?

00:36:56.526 --> 00:36:57.900
There's a sort of
nervous energy,

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:01.460
I think, that managers have that
if they don't feel like they're

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:03.880
active, they feel like
there's something wrong.

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:06.400
And therefore,
that's a huge part

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:08.725
of what leads to how much
micromanagement there is.

00:37:08.725 --> 00:37:10.100
They believe that
they have to be

00:37:10.100 --> 00:37:12.520
actively managing and
managing and controlling.

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:17.530
Which defeats the purpose
of the organization itself.

00:37:17.530 --> 00:37:18.360
Yes, sir?

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:20.230
AUDIENCE: So
WordPress is a company

00:37:20.230 --> 00:37:23.280
where almost everybody
works remotely.

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:27.310
I'd love to hear your thoughts
on how to make a company

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:30.000
culture work where
say, most people

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.020
are in an office and some
people work remotely.

00:37:32.020 --> 00:37:33.620
Like how do you
get the people who

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:35.930
are working remotely plugged
in with the conversation.

00:37:35.930 --> 00:37:39.041
Like what additional
things do they need to do?

00:37:39.041 --> 00:37:40.540
And people in the
office need to do?

00:37:40.540 --> 00:37:42.165
SCOTT BERKUN: So that
is a great point.

00:37:42.165 --> 00:37:45.440
That when you have a company
that has 100% or mostly remote,

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:47.410
some of the
challenges are easier

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:48.500
because everyone's remote.

00:37:48.500 --> 00:37:50.820
So there's no central
office with a bunch

00:37:50.820 --> 00:37:52.270
of people who are
remote workers.

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:55.420
But what that means though is
that during the year and a half

00:37:55.420 --> 00:37:59.080
that I worked there, we
had every different flavor.

00:37:59.080 --> 00:38:01.030
That in some cases,
we'd all be remote.

00:38:01.030 --> 00:38:02.040
That was the majority.

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:03.732
Sometimes we'd all be together.

00:38:03.732 --> 00:38:05.190
Sometimes we'd have
these meet-ups,

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:08.380
but there'd be two or three of
my team that couldn't make it.

00:38:08.380 --> 00:38:11.480
So we'd try, I ended up
with every different dynamic

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:13.660
that I had to figure out.

00:38:13.660 --> 00:38:19.810
My answer is that there has
to be someone, at least one

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:32.160
person, who takes into
account how much is not made--

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:34.900
let me think about
this for a second.

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:38.120
How much of what
goes on in the office

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:41.620
is not manifested all digitally.

00:38:41.620 --> 00:38:43.330
Someone needs to be
thinking about that.

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:45.890
Having had the experience,
or having thought about it,

00:38:45.890 --> 00:38:48.010
if I'm the only remote
worker on a project,

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:51.320
we have our meeting on
Google Hangout or whatever.

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:52.380
We have our meeting.

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:53.550
Now I'm in the meeting,
I'm like, yeah I'm engaged,

00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:55.040
I get what's going on.

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:56.783
Then the next day,
stuff happens and I'm

00:38:56.783 --> 00:38:58.770
like, what the hell's going on.

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:00.430
And what happened is after that
meeting, or that [INAUDIBLE],

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:01.840
there was some
other conversation

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:03.676
in the hallway where
people go, oh, we

00:39:03.676 --> 00:39:05.710
shouldn't do x, we should do y.

00:39:05.710 --> 00:39:07.160
And they start doing y.

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:10.240
Meanwhile, I'm a
thousand miles away

00:39:10.240 --> 00:39:12.100
thinking we're still doing x.

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:14.550
So nobody thought
about how this stuff

00:39:14.550 --> 00:39:17.880
has to be reflected so the
other remote workers can see it.

00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:21.160
Now usually what happens, if
you're the sole remote worker,

00:39:21.160 --> 00:39:23.410
you end up becoming
like Sherlock Holmes.

00:39:23.410 --> 00:39:25.100
Where you're constantly
investigating,

00:39:25.100 --> 00:39:26.445
you're doing like
investigative journalism,

00:39:26.445 --> 00:39:27.840
you're trying to track down.

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:29.210
Hey, did you guys meet after?

00:39:29.210 --> 00:39:29.960
What happened?

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:32.950
You're constantly in this mode
of fear that there's stuff you

00:39:32.950 --> 00:39:34.700
need to know that you don't.

00:39:34.700 --> 00:39:37.110
So the solution is
there has to be someone

00:39:37.110 --> 00:39:41.220
that is in the office,
probably whoever the lead is.

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:44.620
Whoever has more accountability
for the project, who's

00:39:44.620 --> 00:39:48.855
ensuring that that person does
not have to be Sherlock Holmes.

00:39:48.855 --> 00:39:51.920
That they're getting
advice and tips and insight

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:54.250
into what they didn't
capture, because they're not

00:39:54.250 --> 00:39:55.520
in the same building.

00:39:55.520 --> 00:39:57.140
That that stuff gets reflected.

00:39:57.140 --> 00:40:00.660
The easiest way to do that
is if the manifestation

00:40:00.660 --> 00:40:02.570
of the project is digital.

00:40:02.570 --> 00:40:05.414
So we had these habits,
the P2, our blog,

00:40:05.414 --> 00:40:07.580
that was the repository for
all of our conversations

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:09.390
and all of our decisions.

00:40:09.390 --> 00:40:11.934
So even when two
of us might meet,

00:40:11.934 --> 00:40:14.350
our team eventually had eight
or nine people, if two of us

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:16.224
happened to be the same
city at the same time

00:40:16.224 --> 00:40:18.370
and we did some work
together at a whiteboard,

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:21.750
as soon as we were done,
we'd go and post on the blog.

00:40:21.750 --> 00:40:23.610
Hey, Fred and I just
met for an hour,

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:25.760
here's what we just
discussed and decided.

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:27.670
So even though
people weren't there.

00:40:27.670 --> 00:40:29.762
They at least understand
something has changed.

00:40:29.762 --> 00:40:31.845
And didn't just go, Scott,
how could you guys meet

00:40:31.845 --> 00:40:34.560
without-- OK, and then we'd
have a conversation about it.

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:36.410
So the burden is
on the people who

00:40:36.410 --> 00:40:40.645
are in the same shared
space to document.

00:40:40.645 --> 00:40:42.020
AUDIENCE: Makes
sense, thank you.

00:40:42.020 --> 00:40:42.290
SCOTT BERKUN: Yeah, sure.

00:40:42.290 --> 00:40:44.690
AUDIENCE: So I just want to
point out one more thing.

00:40:44.690 --> 00:40:47.250
So Google has a lot
of remote offices,

00:40:47.250 --> 00:40:50.530
so a lot of the insights that
you've just shared with us

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:53.187
and they're in your
book are very relevant

00:40:53.187 --> 00:40:55.270
even though a lot of us
are not working from home.

00:40:55.270 --> 00:40:56.728
I think a lot of
people would agree

00:40:56.728 --> 00:40:59.760
that the relationship between
Mountain View and New York

00:40:59.760 --> 00:41:02.100
and other remote offices
sometimes reflects.

00:41:02.100 --> 00:41:05.755
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure, yeah.

00:41:05.755 --> 00:41:06.499
Yes, sir.

00:41:06.499 --> 00:41:08.290
AUDIENCE: I wonder if
you have any thoughts

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:09.820
about the issues of scale.

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:12.210
I mean I don't know what the
headcount at WordPress was,

00:41:12.210 --> 00:41:14.550
but I assumed it was
probably much smaller

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:15.980
than a place like Google.

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:17.810
Do you think that
a model like that

00:41:17.810 --> 00:41:19.404
could scale up too
many thousands?

00:41:19.404 --> 00:41:21.070
SCOTT BERKUN: Yeah,
I think they it can.

00:41:21.070 --> 00:41:22.300
I think scale is an
interesting question.

00:41:22.300 --> 00:41:24.950
This is one of the most common
questions I've gotten so far.

00:41:24.950 --> 00:41:26.158
Just to give you the numbers.

00:41:26.158 --> 00:41:30.140
So when I was hired in 2010, I
was employee number 58 or so.

00:41:30.140 --> 00:41:34.830
And the time that I left, which
was 2012, the company was 110.

00:41:34.830 --> 00:41:39.070
And now they just crossed 200.

00:41:39.070 --> 00:41:42.920
As best I can tell,
at 200 there's

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:46.260
no signs of scale
affecting any this.

00:41:46.260 --> 00:41:47.780
And I don't think that it will.

00:41:47.780 --> 00:41:49.700
I think that you think
of a product unit

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:53.120
at any organization,
software wise

00:41:53.120 --> 00:41:56.280
or otherwise, a product unit
is about 100 to 200 people.

00:41:56.280 --> 00:41:57.780
You also have
Dunbar's number, which

00:41:57.780 --> 00:42:00.895
is like 250, which says-- I
think that number's probably

00:42:00.895 --> 00:42:01.620
a sweet spot.

00:42:01.620 --> 00:42:05.270
I could imagine if the
company continues to grow,

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:06.569
which it probably will.

00:42:06.569 --> 00:42:08.485
That there may end up
being product units that

00:42:08.485 --> 00:42:10.350
are about 150 to 200 people.

00:42:10.350 --> 00:42:11.680
And there'd be multiple ones.

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:14.090
And at those levels in those
units, it would work fine.

00:42:14.090 --> 00:42:18.290
The challenge with them become
do you have now executives?

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:20.130
Like another level of hierarchy?

00:42:20.130 --> 00:42:23.600
The culture's very
resistance to hierarchy.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:24.835
What would those people do?

00:42:24.835 --> 00:42:27.070
They're not makers anymore.

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:32.030
So now they had this very strong
notion that leads were roles.

00:42:32.030 --> 00:42:33.930
It was not a profession
to be a manager.

00:42:33.930 --> 00:42:35.150
A lead was a role.

00:42:35.150 --> 00:42:37.000
And you need to be in
that role for a while,

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:38.720
but you should have
some other skill set.

00:42:38.720 --> 00:42:41.160
Valve, the game company,
has a similar notion.

00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:44.780
That you're hired because you're
skilled in at least one thing.

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:47.022
So I think that would
be the challenge.

00:42:47.022 --> 00:42:49.480
The other challenge, the other
way they get around this is,

00:42:49.480 --> 00:42:51.230
again, they do
continuous deployment.

00:42:51.230 --> 00:42:53.850
So there's never this
huge dependency tree.

00:42:53.850 --> 00:42:56.197
And that's what usually
causes problems at scale.

00:42:56.197 --> 00:42:57.780
Because you have a
group of 300 people

00:42:57.780 --> 00:43:00.010
that are waiting for this team
of 20 to get something done.

00:43:00.010 --> 00:43:02.051
And that creates all these
logistics and planning

00:43:02.051 --> 00:43:03.650
and any bureaucracy around that.

00:43:03.650 --> 00:43:07.010
And they avoid that because
everything is almost always

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:07.830
live.

00:43:07.830 --> 00:43:11.549
It's very rarely a
huge pile of work

00:43:11.549 --> 00:43:12.840
that is waiting to be deployed.

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:19.630
AUDIENCE: So it's actually
a two part question.

00:43:19.630 --> 00:43:22.067
So the scale example, actually,
I think a lot of people

00:43:22.067 --> 00:43:22.900
were thinking about.

00:43:22.900 --> 00:43:24.700
Its fine when you think
of a small company,

00:43:24.700 --> 00:43:27.010
but what if WordPress starts
releasing other products?

00:43:27.010 --> 00:43:29.790
Like how does accounting,
HR, how does it all work?

00:43:29.790 --> 00:43:31.880
And like the concept
of hiring by trial

00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:34.817
is fine because of
the field they're in.

00:43:34.817 --> 00:43:35.650
How would that work?

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:37.140
Like how did you
interact with HR?

00:43:37.140 --> 00:43:38.850
What if you had an issue
with something else?

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:40.520
It's fine if you're
working development

00:43:40.520 --> 00:43:42.585
and you could do it
offline, and like sync up.

00:43:42.585 --> 00:43:45.040
But HR and things like that.

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:46.910
And the second question
I had is how do you

00:43:46.910 --> 00:43:48.390
evaluate performance?

00:43:48.390 --> 00:43:50.446
SCOTT BERKUN: OK, so
the first question

00:43:50.446 --> 00:43:52.070
I don't really know
how to answer that.

00:43:52.070 --> 00:43:59.710
I mean I think first and
foremost, forget WordPress.com.

00:43:59.710 --> 00:44:06.160
Most things and most
companies don't scale well.

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:08.390
Like most companies fail.

00:44:08.390 --> 00:44:10.570
Most companies go out
of business in a year.

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:13.010
Some crazy statistic
right there.

00:44:13.010 --> 00:44:15.030
Most companies don't scale well.

00:44:15.030 --> 00:44:17.770
You happen to work for one
that has scaled really well,

00:44:17.770 --> 00:44:19.300
that's abnormal.

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:21.050
That's unusual.

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:24.700
So the same challenges
that any organization

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:27.860
has to grow and deal
with growth and scale,

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:30.140
those are big challenges
for any company.

00:44:30.140 --> 00:44:34.010
It's not clear yet how remote
work factors into that or not.

00:44:34.010 --> 00:44:36.330
That's really the best
answer that I can give.

00:44:36.330 --> 00:44:37.790
From my experience
working there,

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:40.050
it seemed like
because of how much

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:43.020
emphasis is placed on
employees, which I think

00:44:43.020 --> 00:44:46.200
could be said about Google's
culture, as well, that

00:44:46.200 --> 00:44:49.820
diminishes risk of scale.

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:52.375
There's very little belief that
added a layer of management

00:44:52.375 --> 00:44:53.740
would solve any kind of problem.

00:44:59.050 --> 00:45:02.300
The second question
about performance.

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:05.920
This is a weird,
fascinating thing.

00:45:05.920 --> 00:45:07.894
I still haven't quite
rationalized in my head.

00:45:07.894 --> 00:45:09.310
There's a bunch
of these questions

00:45:09.310 --> 00:45:13.540
that the book as someone
trying to be a manager,

00:45:13.540 --> 00:45:15.250
I was an outsider
and the book follows

00:45:15.250 --> 00:45:17.219
me trying to sort some
of this stuff out.

00:45:17.219 --> 00:45:18.760
Some of it I still
haven't completely

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:20.840
sorted out how I feel about it.

00:45:20.840 --> 00:45:21.570
Very complicated.

00:45:21.570 --> 00:45:23.160
But the performance thing.

00:45:23.160 --> 00:45:25.860
so the performance
thing, about two months

00:45:25.860 --> 00:45:32.100
into my tenure at
the company, my team

00:45:32.100 --> 00:45:34.040
was actually together
in the same place

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:36.860
and the same physical
location for the first time.

00:45:36.860 --> 00:45:39.535
And we talked about some
stuff and it went fine.

00:45:39.535 --> 00:45:40.910
And I had enough
trust, I thought

00:45:40.910 --> 00:45:43.076
I could start asking some
of these bigger questions.

00:45:43.076 --> 00:45:45.335
I asked my team,
I asked them, how

00:45:45.335 --> 00:45:46.960
do you know if you're
doing a good job?

00:45:49.510 --> 00:45:52.070
And they all looked at each
other and shrugged and went,

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:52.630
I don't know.

00:45:55.850 --> 00:45:56.350
I was, OK.

00:45:59.190 --> 00:46:02.720
At the same time,
that's a bizarre answer,

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:05.340
I kind of expected it.

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:07.400
When you have an
open source project,

00:46:07.400 --> 00:46:10.910
you inherit a whole bunch
of values that are uncommon.

00:46:10.910 --> 00:46:13.880
A lot of the people who
get hired at the company

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:16.540
believe in this project.

00:46:16.540 --> 00:46:19.020
And they worked on
it as a volunteer.

00:46:19.020 --> 00:46:20.530
It was something
they did anyway.

00:46:20.530 --> 00:46:24.500
And now they're hired and get
paid well to work on a project

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:26.140
that they believe in anyway.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:29.890
A project they would help along,
even if it wasn't their job.

00:46:29.890 --> 00:46:33.530
So they're not motivated
by getting a scorecard.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:36.610
They're not motivated
by getting promoted.

00:46:36.610 --> 00:46:38.480
There's not even a lot
of emphasis really,

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:40.640
there's some emphasis,
but not a lot of emphasis,

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:42.890
certainly much less than
your typical company,

00:46:42.890 --> 00:46:45.490
on getting raises.

00:46:45.490 --> 00:46:48.960
People decide that
they want to work here

00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:50.430
after the trial
and all that stuff

00:46:50.430 --> 00:46:54.090
because they really like
the work life balance

00:46:54.090 --> 00:46:56.840
culture that it offers.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:58.710
That you can work
anywhere you want.

00:46:58.710 --> 00:46:59.750
No one cares.

00:46:59.750 --> 00:47:01.252
No one cares about your hours.

00:47:01.252 --> 00:47:02.960
There's that much
independence and you're

00:47:02.960 --> 00:47:05.096
allowed to be good
at what you do.

00:47:05.096 --> 00:47:08.120
So because people are so
happy with that trade,

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:10.360
and it's part of why
they chose to work there.

00:47:10.360 --> 00:47:13.470
These are not the performance
and raises and bonuses,

00:47:13.470 --> 00:47:15.530
all that stuff does
not come up much.

00:47:15.530 --> 00:47:19.720
Now that may be something that
changes five years from now

00:47:19.720 --> 00:47:21.860
when the company maybe
isn't growing as much.

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:25.560
Which is not as much free
reign about what you work on,

00:47:25.560 --> 00:47:28.980
but that remains to be seen.

00:47:28.980 --> 00:47:34.370
Anyway, I worked at Microsoft
for nine years, a decade,

00:47:34.370 --> 00:47:35.020
as an author.

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:36.330
I visit lots of companies.

00:47:36.330 --> 00:47:38.940
I go to lots of places, big
companies, small companies.

00:47:38.940 --> 00:47:40.440
I've never seen a
place where people

00:47:40.440 --> 00:47:48.750
were so happy with the total
trade offs of working there.

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:52.230
These people just
they like what they do

00:47:52.230 --> 00:47:54.110
and they love how
they're treated.

00:47:54.110 --> 00:47:56.770
And they like the trade.

00:47:56.770 --> 00:47:57.865
Their lives are good.

00:47:57.865 --> 00:47:59.740
And they feel they get
that good life because

00:47:59.740 --> 00:48:04.620
of the unusual choices that
Matt Mulleweg and Tony Schneider

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:05.730
at the company have made.

00:48:05.730 --> 00:48:08.470
That was at least
my experience there.

00:48:08.470 --> 00:48:10.880
So their retention's really
high for that reason.

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:12.800
Some people may
want more structure

00:48:12.800 --> 00:48:15.940
and may want a bigger
house and that's

00:48:15.940 --> 00:48:18.170
their focus for why
they have a job.

00:48:18.170 --> 00:48:20.695
They probably wouldn't choose
to go through the trial.

00:48:20.695 --> 00:48:22.111
Because they realize
their culture

00:48:22.111 --> 00:48:24.740
isn't focused on those things.

00:48:24.740 --> 00:48:26.780
Yeah, sure, the mics are open.

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:28.370
AUDIENCE:So the follow-up would
be I think some of the things--

00:48:28.370 --> 00:48:29.745
there's a part
about being happy,

00:48:29.745 --> 00:48:32.042
but then there's also part
about pushing yourself.

00:48:32.042 --> 00:48:33.500
Like a lot of times
in your career,

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:36.277
you get pushed into a stressful
situation and you make it out

00:48:36.277 --> 00:48:38.110
of there, so you know
you're a better person

00:48:38.110 --> 00:48:40.660
but, if I always wanted to be
happy, I'd never force myself--

00:48:40.660 --> 00:48:41.190
SCOTT BERKUN: You're right.

00:48:41.190 --> 00:48:42.190
Happy is the wrong word.

00:48:42.190 --> 00:48:44.310
Fulfillment I think
is a better word.

00:48:44.310 --> 00:48:49.060
But I should say though, that
because these are open source

00:48:49.060 --> 00:48:52.490
cultural roots, on an
open source project ,

00:48:52.490 --> 00:48:54.830
no one's ever really
forcing you to do anything.

00:48:54.830 --> 00:48:55.982
It's a volunteer project.

00:48:55.982 --> 00:48:57.690
And there are certain
pressures depending

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:59.870
on what responsibilities
you've take on.

00:48:59.870 --> 00:49:01.580
But any open source
project always

00:49:01.580 --> 00:49:06.730
has the flavor of volunteerism.

00:49:06.730 --> 00:49:09.990
And that's just rooted in how
the company culture is set up.

00:49:09.990 --> 00:49:14.550
No one really ever, except
in certain situations, that's

00:49:14.550 --> 00:49:17.890
not the fundamental driving
force as an executive,

00:49:17.890 --> 00:49:20.990
say, we must get this done
by Friday otherwise x, or y,

00:49:20.990 --> 00:49:23.880
or it's not like a sports
team where there's, we

00:49:23.880 --> 00:49:25.720
must get points tonight.

00:49:25.720 --> 00:49:29.230
It's that Microsoft
was more like that way.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:32.690
Most American companies have
more of that spirit in them.

00:49:32.690 --> 00:49:35.290
This culture was not like that.

00:49:35.290 --> 00:49:36.665
And for better and for worse.

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:43.430
I don't mean to offer
it as idealized.

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:47.042
I probably would have
more of that personally.

00:49:47.042 --> 00:49:48.750
That there was more
of like a clear goal.

00:49:48.750 --> 00:49:52.200
We had a this high
pressure situation.

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:53.870
I probably would've
liked more of that.

00:49:53.870 --> 00:49:55.245
One of the challenges
in the book

00:49:55.245 --> 00:49:56.750
was one project
that we worked on

00:49:56.750 --> 00:50:01.210
was a project called Jetpack,
which was actually plug-in

00:50:01.210 --> 00:50:03.039
for WordPress that's
an important plug-in,

00:50:03.039 --> 00:50:05.080
but it had to be done by
a certain date and time.

00:50:05.080 --> 00:50:08.479
Which no other project that
my team worked on had to do.

00:50:08.479 --> 00:50:10.020
So that was a
challenge to figure out

00:50:10.020 --> 00:50:11.610
how does this company and
this team that'd never

00:50:11.610 --> 00:50:14.250
worked on a structured project,
or worked on a release cycle,

00:50:14.250 --> 00:50:16.125
how could we figure
out how to do that?

00:50:16.125 --> 00:50:18.500
So there's two chapters in
the book that are all about me

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:23.160
trying to figure out how
to put into place some kind

00:50:23.160 --> 00:50:28.822
of structured process
for making that happen.

00:50:28.822 --> 00:50:30.700
Yeah?

00:50:30.700 --> 00:50:33.330
Last call for
questions, anybody else?

00:50:33.330 --> 00:50:35.340
One more question.

00:50:35.340 --> 00:50:38.170
AUDIENCE: This is maybe a
quick follow-up on that.

00:50:38.170 --> 00:50:42.800
It's open source, but I don't
know the exact business model.

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:45.750
But at some point,
you're hosting,

00:50:45.750 --> 00:50:48.730
you're allowing people to host
their blogs with WordPress.com

00:50:48.730 --> 00:50:52.030
and you have these IRC servers.

00:50:52.030 --> 00:50:54.690
So you have some amount of cost?

00:50:54.690 --> 00:50:55.440
SCOTT BERKUN: Yes.

00:50:55.440 --> 00:50:57.420
AUDIENCE: So you need to
make some amount of money

00:50:57.420 --> 00:50:58.419
to pay for those things?

00:50:58.419 --> 00:51:00.720
So somewhere there's
a motivator to say

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:02.339
this isn't all just volunteers.

00:51:02.339 --> 00:51:03.130
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure.

00:51:03.130 --> 00:51:04.130
AUDIENCE: It's hey,
get things done.

00:51:04.130 --> 00:51:04.540
SCOTT BERKUN: Yes.

00:51:04.540 --> 00:51:05.430
AUDIENCE: Maybe you
could talk to that.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:06.420
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure, absolutely.

00:51:06.420 --> 00:51:07.750
So that was one of
the big questions

00:51:07.750 --> 00:51:08.890
I had going into the company.

00:51:08.890 --> 00:51:10.264
And there's a
chapter in the book

00:51:10.264 --> 00:51:13.337
that talks all about
their business model

00:51:13.337 --> 00:51:15.420
and how they're thinking
about that in the future.

00:51:15.420 --> 00:51:18.760
That the simple answer is that
WordPress is an open source

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:22.570
project that started in 2003,
WordPress.com and the company

00:51:22.570 --> 00:51:26.340
Automatic was formed in 2005.

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:29.606
And the primary ambition was
to solve this hosting issue.

00:51:29.606 --> 00:51:31.230
That WordPress free
software, you still

00:51:31.230 --> 00:51:33.040
have to put it somewhere.

00:51:33.040 --> 00:51:34.950
But it's also a corporation.

00:51:34.950 --> 00:51:36.840
Their ambition is to make money.

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:39.300
And to support WordPress,
but to make money.

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:41.580
WordPress.com makes
money three ways.

00:51:41.580 --> 00:51:43.720
One is through advertising.

00:51:43.720 --> 00:51:45.730
Very small amount
of advertising.

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:49.230
How much that will change as the
company's ambitions, who knows.

00:51:49.230 --> 00:51:50.410
But right now, it's tiny.

00:51:50.410 --> 00:51:52.126
But because of how
much traffic they get,

00:51:52.126 --> 00:51:53.500
it's a substantial
revenue stream

00:51:53.500 --> 00:51:55.160
for a company of 200 people.

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:57.730
Second is upgrades.

00:51:57.730 --> 00:51:59.350
It's a freemium model.

00:51:59.350 --> 00:52:02.350
So if you want more storage
space, you want a better theme,

00:52:02.350 --> 00:52:04.900
you want more
control over CSS, you

00:52:04.900 --> 00:52:07.050
pay a subscription
for those things.

00:52:07.050 --> 00:52:10.780
That's they're most substantial
and probably the most growth

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:14.430
is probably with upgrades
and services around that.

00:52:14.430 --> 00:52:16.660
The third is VIP hosting.

00:52:16.660 --> 00:52:20.730
So there are some premier media
companies and corporations

00:52:20.730 --> 00:52:22.650
that host their blogs
and, in some cases,

00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:26.317
their entire websites on
WordPress.com's architecture.

00:52:26.317 --> 00:52:27.650
And they pay a premium for that.

00:52:27.650 --> 00:52:29.520
It's not a
consumer-oriented service.

00:52:29.520 --> 00:52:31.666
And WordPress.com gets
revenue from that.

00:52:31.666 --> 00:52:33.290
So those are the
three revenue streams.

00:52:33.290 --> 00:52:37.920
Ads, upgrades, and VIP hosting.

00:52:37.920 --> 00:52:40.090
And the book does
talk about this.

00:52:40.090 --> 00:52:44.770
I had this having worked
at most corporations,

00:52:44.770 --> 00:52:47.430
there was a surprisingly
small amount

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:49.590
of pressure on
revenue ambitions.

00:52:49.590 --> 00:52:51.260
In terms of feature direction.

00:52:51.260 --> 00:52:54.090
That most of the
emphasis was on growth,

00:52:54.090 --> 00:52:55.920
not surprising for
a young company,

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:57.690
but they're not young anymore.

00:52:57.690 --> 00:53:00.620
And on activity.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:02.250
So one of my team's
jobs was trying

00:53:02.250 --> 00:53:04.610
to increase to do
user experience design

00:53:04.610 --> 00:53:06.780
work to increase
user engagement.

00:53:06.780 --> 00:53:09.330
How often people posted,
how often people commented,

00:53:09.330 --> 00:53:11.930
that was one of
my teams charters.

00:53:11.930 --> 00:53:14.350
The one other
thing I should say,

00:53:14.350 --> 00:53:18.610
it's been fascinating is
many of these trade offs

00:53:18.610 --> 00:53:22.460
that they have made about giving
employees so much independence

00:53:22.460 --> 00:53:27.080
and these revenue choices
is a very long term vision

00:53:27.080 --> 00:53:30.350
for what WordPress and
WordPress.com should be.

00:53:30.350 --> 00:53:32.630
And I found that inspiring.

00:53:32.630 --> 00:53:35.272
It's very easy to talk
about our long term vision

00:53:35.272 --> 00:53:36.980
and then where is our
quarterly earnings,

00:53:36.980 --> 00:53:38.590
where's our quarterly earnings?

00:53:38.590 --> 00:53:41.720
And most of the decisions
that Matt and Tony made

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:45.360
were-- even if I didn't agree
with them, which in some cases

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:49.260
I didn't, but I understood why
they felt that was in the best

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:51.700
long term interest
of the company

00:53:51.700 --> 00:53:53.852
and the WordPress
project itself.

00:53:53.852 --> 00:53:54.685
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:53:54.685 --> 00:53:57.060
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure.

00:53:57.060 --> 00:53:59.550
OK, well I hope
you guys check out

00:53:59.550 --> 00:54:01.570
the book and thanks
for listening.

00:54:01.570 --> 00:54:02.170
Thanks, yeah.

00:54:02.170 --> 00:54:06.497
[APPLAUSE]

